"Vous connaissez sans doute l'émission « L'amour est dans le pré », mais connaissez-vous « L'amour est dans le champ » ? Contrairement à Karine Lemarchand, ce n'est pas pour un agriculteur que je recherche le partenaire idéal, mais pour une variété de blé. En fait, j'étudie la génétique des légumineuses, et plus précisément, la génétique du petit pois. Et dans ma thèse, je tente de déterminer le petit pois idéal pour les cultures pois-blé.

Mais alors, pourquoi tenter de marier une variété de pois avec une variété de blé ? Eh bien, mes collègues scientifiques ont déjà montré que ce type de culture permettait d'améliorer le rendement global, mais également de mieux maîtriser les mauvaises herbes. Mais d'ailleurs, pourquoi mauvaises ? Eh bien, tout simplement parce qu'elles rentrent en compétition avec le blé pour la lumière, et donc freinent son développement.

Mais alors maintenant, pour identifier ce partenaire idéal pour lutter contre les mauvaises herbes, comment allons-nous procéder concrètement ? Tout d'abord, le nombre de variétés de pois existantes est bien trop important. Il est donc inconcevable de tester l'ensemble des candidats potentiels. Il va donc falloir effectuer une première sélection parmi ces derniers.

Nous allons donc présenter à notre variété de blé un nombre restreint de candidats, mais avec des profils très différents. On peut donc imaginer un premier prétendant de pois, grand, beau, productif, somme tout très séduisant, mais très dressé. Un second, plus chétif, moins sexy, plus Robert que Redford, mais présentant tout de même une bonne couverture du sol.

L'objectif ici, en comparant le résultat obtenu par nos deux prétendants, est de définir un profil, un ensemble de caractéristiques qui garantissent à notre pois d'être un bon compétiteur vis-à-vis des mauvaises herbes. Or, dans mes travaux, j'ai confirmé que la capacité de la plante à recouvrir le sol nu à l'aide de sa végétation, aidait dans la lutte contre les mauvaises herbes.

En fait, plus un pois sera couvrant, moins les mauvaises herbes auront accès à la lumière, et donc moins elles pourront se développer. Alors maintenant que nous avons identifié que ce pouvoir couvrant était un caractère majeur dans la lutte contre les mauvaises herbes, je vais cette fois tester un grand nombre de variétés de pois, 170, et originaires de toute l'Europe.

Ces 170 variétés de pois présentent elles aussi des caractéristiques très différentes, mais cette fois, j'ai également le choix de la plante, et également déterminé le patrimoine génétique de l'ensemble de mes candidats. Finalement, je peux comparer cette information génétique avec la quantité de mauvaises herbes présentes dans chacune de mes parcelles pois-blé, et ainsi déterminer quel gène prendre en compte pour avoir un bon prétendant, un prétendant qui ne laisse pas la place aux mauvaises herbes de se développer.

Et c'est ainsi que je compte présenter à notre variété de blé, un partenaire de pois."

Since the dawn of time, there has been a secret war that has already claimed millions of lives. I myself have lost some comrades, and no doubt you have too. I especially think of the young foals who lived on the farm next to my parents' when I was younger, and unfortunately did not survive. In this war, we have a common enemy. We humans, but also animals, whether terrestrial or marine, with insects, birds, and even plants. This common enemy is the parasitic worm. Parasitic worms are everywhere and come in all shapes and sizes. Some are microscopic and live in soil, and those are very good for the environment. On the other hand, others are very nasty and parasitize almost all living species on this planet. In humans, one person out of two has been infested or was infested. So look at your neighbor to your left, your neighbor to your right. If it's not you, maybe your neighbor is infested. I can't take care of all the parasites that exist on this earth, so I'm going to focus on the one that traumatized me in my childhood. This worm, in horses, causes respiratory and digestive problems and can lead to animal death. We do have an arm against this worm, a molecule called ivermectin. Ivermectin was commercialized in the 80s, so it's been around for 40 years. And that's where the problem is. Just like antibiotics and bacteria, worms have developed resistances to this molecule. And that's where I come in. The goal of my thesis is to understand how ivermectin works on this parasite, because we still don't know at this point, even after 40 years, and to understand the resistance mechanisms involved against this molecule to develop new strategies for fighting it. So we do have some leads. We know that ivermectin acts on the nervous system of the worm, specifically on receptors. These receptors are composed of five subunits, like five fingers, and allow or block a neural message depending on whether the receptor opens or closes. The parasite has an idea, like move, eat, reproduce. The idea passes through this receptor and triggers action, eating, moving, reproducing. Ivermectin will bind to this receptor and prevent the worm from realizing its actions. The worm is paralyzed and will die. But if the worm is resistant, ivermectin won't be able to bind to the receptor, and the worm will live freely in the horse. So the goal of my thesis is already to identify these receptors and find the right subunit composition so that the receptor is functional, and then study the interactions between this receptor and the molecule involved, which is used to treat this parasite. In a second step, I will focus on the mutations of resistance that exist on this receptor to develop a new strategy and bypass the resistance. So you can count on me to save the ponies; I'll give it my all.

Do you know that 99% of our oranges today are imported from California? But do you also know that, about 150 years ago, it was California that was importing its oranges from Tahiti? And this is just one example of many that characterizes this little-known American-Tahitian relationship. I am writing a thesis on Americans in the 19th century in Tahiti and the islands of current French Polynesia. And often, history books about Polynesian relate the Franco-British rivalry over Tahiti, but forget the presence of Americans at the same time. Americans who were building the superpower they would become in the 20th century. And that's where I come in. I want to develop the idea of a once-American island, Tahiti, and the intense relationship between Americans and Polynesians, not recognized by the French, which still keeps the memory of British influence in this island. My research on archival documents provides initial results. The Yankees, as they were called at the time, were numerous in the five archipelagos of current French Polynesia. And these islands were American before being French. Not an American colony, even if in 1813, Commodore David Porter annexes Nuku Hiva on his own initiative without Washington's approval. And you see here one of the few period engravings showing an American flag planted on Marquesan soil. But rather an American influence and a strong impact before the French protectorate and annexation. Furthermore, American whaling ships were nearly ten times more numerous than those from other nations in the port of Papeete between 1830 and 1840. And that's where you find the idea of an American colony. In 1854, nineteen whaling ships arrived in Papeete. Among them, one Frenchman, one Englishman, and all the others were... Americans. The following year, Tahiti received two French whaling ships, a Brazilian ship, and eleven... and yes, eleven American whaling ships. One can imagine then the economic impact but also social impact of this presence. Additionally, American evangelization in Tahiti and the islands led to the late 19th century anchoring of three American religions that make some Polynesians still today Mormons, Adventists, and Seventh-day Adventists. My goal is therefore to introduce the Polynesian people to their own recent history, which is part of their near past. For integrating one's own nearby history and knowing the sometimes foreign origin of some ancestors can enable Polynesians to fully assume their history and serene their entire identity. Thank you.

That's one aspect I'm dealing with in my thesis and that we're going to see together. The objective of this thesis is to be able to give functionality and effectiveness back to these plans. So what's wrong with the notion of radicalization since it's what's causing the problem? First, it has no structure, neither legal nor scientific. For example, in my thesis, I looked at the national plan for preventing radicalization published by the government in 2018. And you can see that word "radicalization" used 112 times without ever defining what it means. As a result, you're free to interpret this notion however you like. That's it. That's the first point. Secondly, the notion of radicalization disqualifies. It accuses. And by doing so, it adds more emotion, more sensation, and never any sense. That's the second point. And the third point is that... The notion of radicalization does not distinguish well between what is moral and what is legal. If a woman wants to wear a hijab, one day you can suspect her of being radicalized or Islamist. But does she have the legal right to do so? Yes. So accusing someone of doing something legally allowed, that's suspicious. What can we do? First, we need to give more responsibility to the notion of radicalization. Reference to law because law is identifiable, morality is not. I can find a legal text, but not a moral one. Then, we can't leave on the same plan and with the same term the radicalization of someone who might be going to war and another person who is just living in... That's not possible. And then, we need to change our way of defining things. Talking about radicalization is too vague. Talking about violent activism is more precise. Talking about Salafism doesn't teach us anything. I study nuclei to understand stars. My domain is nuclear astrophysics. Astrophysics is the study of planets, stars, and galaxies - the study of the infinitely large. On the other hand, nuclear physics is the study of the nuclei of atoms that make up everything around us - the study of the infinitely small. So how can studying these nuclei help us understand what happens in stars? This question has not been recent for 100 years. In fact, it was asked by a French physicist and Nobel laureate, Jean Perrin, 100 years ago. At the time, we did not know how the heat and light of the Sun were produced. Today, we know that it is due to the transformation of four hydrogen nuclei into one helium nucleus. During this transformation, known as a nuclear reaction, a part of their mass is transformed into energy. That's the famous equation E equals mc2. If the energy emitted during this reaction had been slightly different, the heat of the Sun would not have been the same. It might be cold. There may be no life on Earth. I would not be here to talk to you about it and you would not be here to listen to me.

If studying nuclear reactions has allowed us to understand the Sun, it is the same for all stars. In my thesis, I was interested in two interacting stars - one that resembles our Sun and another called a neutron star. A neutron star is what remains after a supernova, which is the violent death of a star. We will find ourselves with a small-sized star, since its size is not much greater than the Paris region, but it has a very important mass. Its mass is greater than that of our Sun. The nuclei of the other star that resembles our Sun will then be attracted to this neutron star, accumulate around it, and eventually, at a certain moment, the pressure will increase and trigger an explosion. During this explosion, there will be emission of X-rays that we can detect on Earth using satellites.

In fact, American scientists in the 1970s were a bit worried because they had spy satellites and thought they detected a nuclear explosion every day. Today, they are reassured thanks to astrophysicists like us. These same astrophysicists will try to reproduce these explosions theoretically on computer using mathematical formulas. But for that, they will need to understand all the nuclear reactions that took place during this explosion.
